1. Introduction

As a person living in the Silicon valley bay area for the last 5 years, Ive always missed the better availability of public transport. That being said, driving a car is inevitable and necessary. I had a perfect driving record up until August this year when I was involved in a fender-bender just outside my garage! Although, the insurance covered it but it did feel bad to being in an accident. Accidents can happen even to the most careful among us and when accidents do happen, auto insurance is the only thing that can save us from a loto of personal liabilities which we are otherwise quite expensive. I have visited a few of the cities in the country and have seen a noticeable difference in driving style, driver tolerance and other factors. This piked my interest in exploring how different states in the USA compare to each other w.r.t driving quality and how drivers. We know car Insurance premium varies from driver to driver and there are lots of variables at work behind that, for example: age of the driver, driving record etc. We also pay higher or lower insurance depending on which state we live in. Can we predict the average insurance premiums for states from the driving record of that state.

In this report I will be conducting data analysis on the Bad Drivers dataset from FiveThirtyEights dataset library. It compares the data of fatal collisions in all the states due to different regions. Some of the basic questions I want to get answers to are which state has the highest number of collisions in the country or is there a more likely reason of maximum fatal collisions. Also, we will pick two variables from the data and try to predict average car insurance premiums using those two variables and compare them with actual data.

2. Data

Data Source:

The data was collected from https://github.com/fivethirtyeight/data/tree/master/bad-drivers.

Variables:

  1. State- Each state in United States
  2. Number of drivers involved in fatal collisions per billion miles
  3. Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Speeding
  4. Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Alcohol-Impaired
  5. Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Not Distracted
  6. Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Had Not Been Involved In Any Previous Accidents
  7. Car Insurance Premiums ($)
  8. Losses incurred by insurance companies for collisions per insured driver ($)

Cases:

There are 52 cases, 1 for each of the 51 states with 8 variables.

Type of Study:

The study is observational and the data is collected based on what is seen without any interference. The data represents entire population of U.S. drivers. Thus, the data is generalized to the entire U.S. population.

3. Exploratory Data Analysis

Which state has the highest number of drivers involved in fatal collisions per billion miles? 

plot1 <- ggplot(data = indata2) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = num_driver_fatal, y = state)) + scale_y_discrete(expand=c(0.002, 0.002))

plot1+ labs(x = "Number of drivers involved in fatal collisions", y = "State", 
                  title = "Drivers involved in fatal collisions in each state ") + theme(axis.text.y=element_text(angle=0,hjust=1,vjust=0))

Insights:

The plot shows us that North Dakota, South Carolina and West Virgina are the three states that have highest number of drivers involved in fatal collisions per billion miles.

Which state has the highest number of drivers involved in fatal collisions due to speeding?

Hypothesis testing for fatalities caused due to Speeding

H0: mu=30.5 , H1: mu>30.5

speeding <- indata2$percent_speeding
 mean_speeding <- mean(speeding)
 sd_percent_speeding <- sd(speeding)
 mean_speeding
## [1] 31.72549
 sd_percent_speeding
## [1] 9.633438
 t.test(speeding, mu= 30.5)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  speeding
## t = 0.90848, df = 50, p-value = 0.368
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 30.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  29.01604 34.43494
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  31.72549

Insights:

Since the p-value is low, we can reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the alternate is true and the mean is above 30.5.

Linear Regression model to find relation between insurance premiums and drivers involved in fatal collisions 

linreg1 <- lm(formula = insur_prem ~ num_driver_fatal, data = indata2)
summary(linreg1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = insur_prem ~ num_driver_fatal, data = indata2)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -249.23 -136.43  -22.29  133.45  435.28 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                  Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)      1023.354     98.748  10.363 6.08e-14 ***
## num_driver_fatal   -8.638      6.055  -1.427     0.16    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 176.5 on 49 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.03988,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.02029 
## F-statistic: 2.035 on 1 and 49 DF,  p-value: 0.16
plot(indata2$insur_prem ~ indata2$num_driver_fatal)
abline(linreg1)

cor( indata2$insur_prem, indata2$num_driver_fatal)
## [1] -0.1997019

Insights:

If the number of drivers who are involved in a fatal collision per billion miles increase by 1 then the Insurance premium decreases by around $8.64. The variance of 3.99% of the response variable Insurance premium (insur_prem) can be explained by explanatory variable Total fatal collisions (num_driver_fatal). The plot above shows that there is a very weak (due to large deviance of datapoints from the line) negative linear relationship between the 2 variables.

How does insurance company cover for their losses? 

linreg2 <- lm(formula = insur_prem ~ loss_per_insur_driver, data = indata2)
summary(linreg2)
##

## lm(formula = insur_prem ~ loss_per_insur_driver, data = indata2)

plot(indata2$insur_prem ~ indata2$loss_per_insur_driver)
abline(linreg2)

cor( indata2$insur_prem, indata2$loss_per_insur_driver)
## [1] 0.6231164

Insights:

For every Dollar increase in losses incurred by the insurance companies the insurance premimum goes up by $4.4733 and around 38.83% of the variance found in the response variable Insurance premium (insur_prem) can be explained by this predictor variable Losses incurred by insurance companies for collisions per insured driver (loss_per_insur_driver). There is a moderate positive linear relationship between the two variables.

5. Conclusion

From my data analysis of Bad Drivers Dataset, I found out that the top 3 states with highest number of drivers involved in fatal collisions per billion miles are North Dakota, South Carolina and West Virgina. The Analysis also shows that speeding is not the top reason for fatal collisions in the either of those 3 states. Instead, Hawaii is the state with maximum number of collisions due to speeding. Talking about changes in auto insurance premiums, for every dollar increase in losses incurred by insurance companies, the premium goes up by $4.5. Another thing that I found out with this analysis is if the number of drivers who are involved in a fatal collision per billion miles increase then the Insurance premium decreases by around $8.64. This sounds a bit odd so a deeper research and analysing other data sets in this field might give more accurate results.
